Title:
Invoke-NetLoader

Type:
GitHub Tool

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
Invoke-NetLoader is a PowerShell wrapper around Flangvik’s NetLoader, inspired by PowerSharpPack-style in-memory execution workflows. It is designed to help operators load and execute arbitrary C#/.NET binaries via PowerShell, with the stated intent of combining it with PowerShell obfuscation and AMSI bypass techniques to evade AV/EDR. The repository primarily provides a single PowerShell script (`Invoke-NetLoader.ps1`) plus a brief README and usage example. It’s most useful for red teams and pentesters who need a flexible .NET payload loader in post-exploitation scenarios. The interesting aspect is the focus on integrating a known .NET loader into a PowerShell-based tradecraft chain (obfuscation + AMSI bypass + in-memory execution).

Technical Focus:
- PowerShell-based .NET payload loading
- In-memory execution of C# assemblies
- AMSI bypass integration (operator-supplied)
- PowerShell obfuscation compatibility
- NetLoader/PowerSharpPack-style execution patterns

Use Cases:
- Execute C# post-exploitation tooling from PowerShell without writing binaries to disk
- Wrap and deliver .NET tradecraft through PowerShell launchers
- Combine with AMSI bypass + script obfuscation for AV/EDR evasion testing
- Rapid operator workflow for loading multiple .NET utilities during engagements

Keywords:
PowerShell, Invoke-NetLoader, NetLoader, PowerSharpPack, .NET, C#, in-memory execution, assembly loading, AMSI, AMSI bypass, obfuscation, AV evasion, EDR evasion, post-exploitation, loader, red team, pentest, Windows, offensive tooling